<li id="cite_note-148"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-148">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web">Craig Rusbult, Ph.D. (1998). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.asa3.org/ASA/education/origins/te2-cr.htm">"Evolutionary Creation"</a>. American Scientific Affiliation<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.asa3.org/ASA/education/origins/te2-cr.htm">http://www.asa3.org/ASA/education/origins/te2-cr.htm</a></span>. "A theory of theistic evolution (TE) — also called evolutionary creation * — proposes that God's method of creation was to cleverly design a universe in which everything would naturally evolve. Usually the "evolution" in "theistic evolution" means Total Evolution — astronomical evolution (to form galaxies, solar systems,...) and geological evolution (to form the earth's geology) plus chemical evolution (to form the first life) and biological evolution (for the development of life) — but it can refer only to biological evolution."</span></span></li>
